{"text": "﻿EXAM:
  CT Angiography Chest With Intravenous Contrast.

CLINICAL HISTORY:
  76 years old, female; Pain; Chest pain; Type not specified

TECHNIQUE:
  Axial computed tomographic angiography images of the chest with intravenous contrast using pulmonary embolism protocol.
  Coronal and sagittal reformatted images were created and reviewed.

EXAM DATE/TIME:
  3/22/2017 1:51 AM

COMPARISON:
  No relevant prior studies available.

FINDINGS:
  Pulmonary arteries:  No evidence of pulmonary embolism.
  Aorta:  No acute findings.  No thoracic aortic aneurysm.
  Lungs:  There are a few scattered bilateral pulmonary nodules measuring 4 mm or less.  Mild dependent and scattered subsegmental atelectasis bilaterally.  Moderate centrilobular emphysema.
  Pleural space:  No significant pleural effusion.  No pneumothorax.
  Heart:  Atherosclerotic calcifications affect the coronary arteries.  No cardiomegaly or pericardial effusion.
  Bones/joints:  No acute fracture.   
  Soft tissues:  Unremarkable.
  Lymph nodes:  Mild right hilar adenopathy measuring up to 1.1 cm, nonspecific.

IMPRESSION:     
1.  No evidence of pulmonary embolism.  
2.  There are a few scattered bilateral pulmonary nodules measuring 4 mm or less.  
3.  Mild right hilar adenopathy measuring up to 1.1 cm, nonspecific.  

As per Fleischner Society guidelines for follow-up and management of pulmonary nodules:

For patients at low risk (minimal or absent history of smoking and of other known risk factors), no follow-up needed.

For patients at high risk (history of smoking or of other known risk factors), recommend follow-up chest CT at 12 months; if unchanged, no further follow-up needed.
"}
